  "prompt": "What is the lowest temperature to leave a thermostat so that the pipes don't freeze?",
  "response": "The commonly recommended lowest temperature to set your thermostat to prevent pipes from freezing is **55\u00b0F (13\u00b0C)**.\n\nWhile some people might get away with slightly lower temperatures in well-insulated homes or milder climates, 55\u00b0F provides a good safety margin to protect your plumbing.  Here's why:\n\n*   **Pipes in exterior walls and uninsulated areas are most vulnerable:** These areas are more susceptible to temperature drops.\n*   **Air temperature vs. pipe temperature:** The air temperature near the thermostat doesn't necessarily reflect the temperature inside the walls where your pipes are located.\n*   **Wind chill:** Strong winds can significantly lower the temperature of exposed pipes.\n*   **Cost of repairs:** The cost of repairing frozen and burst pipes far outweighs the cost of maintaining a slightly warmer temperature.\n\n**Other precautions:**\n\n*   **Insulate pipes:** Especially those in unheated or poorly insulated areas.\n*   **Seal cracks and openings:** Reduce drafts that can make pipes colder.\n*   **Let faucets drip:** A slow, steady drip of both hot and cold water can help prevent pipes from freezing. This is especially helpful in areas with extremely cold temperatures.\n*   **Open cabinet doors:** Allow warm air to circulate around pipes under sinks and in exterior walls.\n\n**Important Note:** This is a general guideline. If you live in an area with consistently very cold temperatures, you might need to set your thermostat higher.  Also, if you are going to be away for an extended period, consider having someone check on your home regularly.\n\nIn conclusion, while 55\u00b0F is a common recommendation, it's best to consider your specific situation and local weather conditions to determine the safest temperature for your home.\n",
